Paragraph or block, is main element that helps with document structuring. It serves as container for all other elements.

## Paragraph properties
Paragraph properties serve to determine the appearance and behavior of a selected paragraph. In addition to alignment and indentation, the behavior relative to the previous or the following paragraph can be controlled. Thus you can set whether these paragraphs stay together or not when an automatic page break occurs.

To get to the paragraph properties, select the respective paragraph in the editor and go to the right panel &gt; Styles &gt; Paragraph Properties.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Paragraph Properties*

This panel contains the following properties you can set:

- Alignment

Defines paragraph alignment properties and contains the following choices:

Left

- Center

- Right

- Justify

- Margin top/bottom/left/right

Defines the distances, on all sides, from the padding rectangle to the outer edges of the border rectangle. The border rectangle contains the padding rectangle plus the areas delineated by its margin distances.

- Padding top/bottom/left/right

Defines the distances, on all sides, from the content rectangle to the inner edges of the border rectangle. The padding rectangle contains the content rectangle plus the areas delineated by its padding distances.

- Keep together

Tries to keep the entire paragraph in one piece on the same page.

- Keep together with previous

The end of the previous paragraph should be on the same page as the start of the current paragraph.

- Keep together with next

The next paragraph should begin after the current on the same page.

> Keep in mind that when two or more paragraphs are kept together, each empty line counts as one paragraph. In particular if two paragraphs separated by an empty line should stay on one page, you must set for the empty line at least one of the two 'keep with' options. If you use both these options the empty line then the other relevant paragraphs need no further settings. Do not forget: Keeps work with Breaks and come into play when a page break occurs (either an explicit one or an automatic one generated by the FO formatter).
